        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Pelvic Imaging Following Chemotherapy and Radiation Therapy for Gynecologic Malignancies1" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Helen C.  Addley" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Hebert Alberto  Vargas" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Penelope L.  Moyle" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Robin  Crawford" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Evis  Sala" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="The use of chemotherapy and radiation therapy in the treatment of gynecologic malignancies is reviewed, radiation therapy planning is described, and the expected posttreatment imaging appearances o..." /><meta name="Description" content="The use of chemotherapy and radiation therapy in the treatment of gynecologic malignancies is reviewed, radiation therapy planning is described, and the expected posttreatment imaging appearances o..." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Gynecologic malignancies account for 10%–15% of all malignancies in females. A variety of oncologic options are available depending on organ of origin, histologic diagnosis, and disease grade and s..." /><meta name="Description" content="Gynecologic malignancies account for 10%–15% of all malignancies in females. A variety of oncologic options are available depending on organ of origin, histologic diagnosis, and disease grade and s..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content="Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2010-11-01" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="105063" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.307105063" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.307105063" /><meta name="dc.Language" content="en" /><meta name="dc.Coverage" content